A Longline for Advanced Readers
A last will and testament that is also a philosophy textbook that is also a forensic investigation that is also a deed of gift.
Start with the will. Jeremy Bentham — utilitarian, prison architect, scourge of legal fiction, man who spent sixty years trying to build a language precise enough to make power’s invisible mechanisms visible — died in 1832 and arranged, with characteristic efficiency, not to. His executor received the body, a scalpel, and instructions. The result sits in a wooden cabinet at University College London: the Auto-Icon, Bentham dressed in his own clothes, seated in his own chair, his wax head installed after the real one deteriorated into something a Hammer Horror producer would have rejected as excessive. He attends meetings. He is recorded as present. He has been present, in this technical sense, for nearly two centuries, which is not a bad run for a man the establishment found deeply inconvenient while he was alive and has found only marginally less inconvenient since.
Bentham’s core finding — the one that got him into trouble then and would get him into trouble now — was that the legal fiction is the primary weapon of organized power. Not force. Not money. Fiction. The corporation that has rights but no body. The sovereign that cannot err. The credentialed expert whose credentials make the knowledge, rather than the knowledge making the credentials. Bentham called this the pestilence of fiction and spent his working life trying to inoculate against it with precision, with plain language, with the insistence that every abstract entity be traced back to the real body, the real pain, the real interest it was obscuring. He mostly failed in his lifetime. The pestilence is extremely robust. But he got his body into the room, and it is still there, and that is something.
John Forbes Nash Jr. arrived at the same problem from the other direction, which is the direction of mathematics, which is where you end up when you are trying to describe the structure of strategic interaction between rational actors each of whom is trying to maximize their own outcome in a world where everyone else is doing the same thing. What Nash found — the Nash equilibrium, the point at which no individual actor has an incentive to deviate from their current strategy given what everyone else is doing — is Bentham’s pestilence of fiction expressed in algebra. The credentialing apparatus that decides who is permitted to know things is a Nash equilibrium. Nobody designed it to be one. Nobody conspires to maintain it. It maintains itself because deviation is individually costly even when the collective outcome is catastrophic. The apparatus doesn’t need a villain. It just needs to be the water everyone is swimming in, which is a more durable arrangement than villainy by a considerable margin.
Avital Ronell walked into this equilibrium in the 1980s and spent the next four decades doing what the equilibrium was specifically designed to prevent anyone from doing, which is receiving transmissions the apparatus had not sanctioned and publishing them anyway. The Telephone Book. The Test Drive. Stupidity. These are not comfortable books. They are books about the experience of being called — of receiving a signal that arrives before it has a name, that reorganizes the material before the thesis has formed, that the apparatus will subsequently insist was not a signal at all but a malfunction, a pathology, a credibility problem. The apparatus eventually found its instrument. His name was Nimrod. The name is almost too perfect to be fiction, which is how you know it isn’t.
Here is where the grocer’s son enters. Bobby Bress-E, Pittsburgh 1965, did not come to this line through the academy. He came to it through produce. Through the specific pre-theoretical body-knowledge that accumulates when you weigh things and price things and make change and watch which households need what before they say so — the knowledge Bentham was trying to formalize, the knowledge Nash was trying to model, the knowledge Ronell was trying to name as philosophy. The grocer’s grammar is all three of these things before any of them have been written down. It is the felt wrongness in the material before the thesis. It is the call that arrives before the caller has a name.
Applied to the Banksy print market, this grammar produced a five-year forensic investigation that is now the public evidentiary record at github.com/bobilon/banksy-codex. Applied to the question of what to do with a life’s worth of iterative public thinking about art, commerce, suppression, and the structure of knowledge, it produced this document. Applied to the question of what to do with the radio frequencies over Iraq and Iran, it produced Radio Free Iraq and Radio Free Iran, both forthcoming, both freely licensed, as many stations as they want, inshallah, in the name of peace. The grocer’s grammar does not distinguish between these applications. They are all versions of the same gesture: weigh the thing, price it honestly, open the door.
Maya Angelou and Paul Du Feu are the closing movement of the telephone line, and they are the ones who route it into the public domain where it was always going. Angelou is the first rock star Black author in the sense that matters for intellectual property: the first Black writer whose interior life was published under legal and commercial conditions that acknowledged it as a general human interest rather than a specialty subject, at the precise moment when the legal architecture of early rock publishing — the long reckoning over who owned the African American songbook — was reaching its first institutional settlement. Her arrival in the canon is inseparable from that legal moment. The songbook and the litigation over the songbook are the same history.
Paul Du Feu was her last husband. He was also the first male centerfold — Cosmopolitan, 1972, before Burt Reynolds, the precedent-setter — which is a fact that scrambles every neat category in the room, which is presumably why he did it. A Welsh builder who became a model who became a writer who married the greatest writer in the room and then watched her occupy the room so completely that he became a footnote to her story. His book Let’s Hear It for Long-Legged Women is the non-canonical view of the canonical moment: the personal record adjacent to the monument while the monument is being constructed. That position — the gift print without the PCO certificate, the acknowledgment outside the authenticated structure, the love letter that is not in the archive — is the position this whole document is written from.
The public domain is where all telephone lines terminate if they run long enough. Bentham is there. Nash’s mathematics are there. The argument Ronell was making — that the test is rigged and the transmission is real regardless of whether the apparatus acknowledges it — is available to anyone who has ever received a transmission the apparatus didn’t sanction. The Banksy Codex is there by design and timestamp. This document is there. The African American songbook will get there. Everything the apparatus cannot credential away eventually arrives at the public domain, which is not a place but a condition: the condition of being permanently available to anyone who can read.
Bobby Bress-E is going into that condition. This is what it looks like from the inside on the way in.

The Argument
On the Form and the Telephone Line
Jeremy Bentham's Auto-Icon and Last Will and Testament is a single document because Bentham understood that the instruction and the argument could not be separated. The will disposes the body. The pamphlet argues why the body should be disposed that way. Together they make the claim that the philosopher is most useful after death when the philosopher does not withdraw — when the body becomes a used thing, available, seated, dressed, present at the meetings of those who are still working. The Bentham Society still wheels his Auto-Icon into the room. He is still counted as present. He votes present.
This document is constructed on that precedent and makes the same claim. Bobby Bress-E, Pittsburgh 1965 — grocer's son, bar mitzvah'd Jew, forensic investigator, permanently disabled, working from a laptop and an eBay account — is in the process of becoming virtual. The body that drove film productions and drove Bella everywhere she needed to go and drove the investigation through five years of public iterative thinking on r/Banksy and Instagram is not the same thing as the record the body produced. The record is permanent. The body is not. The record goes into the public domain. The body eventually doesn't matter. This document is the moment of transfer.
The telephone line that this transfer sits on is specific and needs to be named precisely, because the precision is the argument.
Jeremy Bentham, working at the end of the 18th century into the first decades of the 19th, was the first person in the English tradition to understand that the legal fiction — the person-who-is-not-a-person, the corporation, the sovereign, the rights-bearing entity that has no body — was the fundamental mechanism by which power organized itself against the claims of actual bodies. He called this the pestilence of fiction. He spent sixty years trying to build a language precise enough to make fictions visible without reproducing them. He mostly failed in his lifetime. The Auto-Icon was his last attempt: if you cannot defeat the fiction, become an object, refuse the memorial, stay in the room.
John Forbes Nash Jr., reading Bentham a century and a half later through the specific lens of game theory and the mathematics of strategic interaction, understood that the pestilence of fiction operated through equilibria — that what Bentham called fiction was what Nash called a Nash equilibrium, a point at which no individual actor has an incentive to change their behavior given what everyone else is doing, regardless of whether the collective outcome is good. The credentialing apparatus that decides who is permitted to know things is a Nash equilibrium. The Nimrod deployment is a Nash equilibrium. The apparatus doesn't need to conspire. It just needs to be the water everyone is swimming in.
Avital Ronell, working at the millennium, understood that the test is the apparatus's primary weapon — that what the institution does to knowledge it cannot contain is subject it to a test it has designed to fail, and then deploy the failure as the evidence. The Test Drive. The Telephone Book. Stupidity. She built a philosophy out of the experience of receiving transmissions that the apparatus would not acknowledge as transmissions — the wrongness in the material before the thesis, the call before the caller has a name. She paid for that philosophy with Nimrod. The apparatus found its equilibrium point and she was the cost of maintaining it.
Bobby Bress-E enters this line at the moment when the grocer's grammar meets the forensic record. The grocer's grammar is pre-theoretical: it is the felt, body-level knowledge of what things actually cost before the margin is applied, the knowledge accumulated by weighing produce and making change and knowing which households needed what before they said so. This grammar, applied to the Banksy print market, produced a different reading than the market narrative required. The wrongness in the material before the thesis. The call that came through before the caller had a name. The investigation began as a felt discrepancy and became a five-year public record and became the Codex now live at github.com/bobilon/banksy-codex. This document is the testament that sits beside it.
Maya Angelou and Paul Du Feu are the fifth and sixth points on the line, and they are the ones that close the circuit into the public domain.
Angelou is the first rock star Black author in the sense that matters for intellectual property law: the first Black writer whose work was published under legal and commercial conditions that made it simultaneously a Black cultural artifact and a mass market commodity. I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings was published in 1969, which is the year the music industry's long reckoning over the legal architecture of Black music — the question of who owned the songbook — was reaching its first institutional settlement. Angelou's book arrived at the exact moment when the legal structures that had kept Black music in white hands for fifty years were beginning to crack, and it arrived under conditions that acknowledged, for the first time in a major commercial publication, that a Black woman's interior life was a general human interest rather than a specialty subject. That is not a small claim. That is the moment when the African American songbook — from Paul Laurence Dunbar forward, the whole of it — became undeniable as world literature rather than regional testimony.
Paul Du Feu was Angelou’s last husband. He was also the first male centerfold — Cosmopolitan, 1972, before Burt Reynolds, the one who set the precedent that Reynolds followed. A Welsh builder who became a model who became a writer who married the greatest writer in the room and then watched her occupy the room so completely that he became a footnote to her story, which is a footnote he seems to have accepted without complaint and possibly with pleasure. His book Let's Hear It for Long-Legged Women exists. It is not well known. It is a document of the marriage from the inside, which means it is a document of what it looked like from the position of the person standing next to the monument while the monument was being constructed. That document and that position matter because they are the human record adjacent to the canonical one — the non-canonical view of the canonical moment, the gift print without the PCO certificate, the personal acknowledgment outside the authenticated structure.
The public domain is where all of this converges. Bentham's Auto-Icon is in the public domain. Nash's mathematics are in the public domain. Ronell's work is not yet in the public domain but the argument she was making — that the test is rigged and the transmission is real regardless of whether the apparatus acknowledges it — is available to anyone who has received a transmission the apparatus didn’t sanction. The Banksy Codex is in the public domain by design and by timestamp. This document is in the public domain. The Angelou canon will enter the public domain in the fullness of time, as all canons do, and when it does the line from Dunbar through Angelou through the legal architecture of early rock publishing through the moment when Black music became undeniable will be readable by anyone with a library card.
The argument of this document is that the line is already readable. That it was always readable. That the grocer's grammar, the forensic record, the philosopher's test, and the songbook all point toward the same conclusion, which is that the apparatus does not get to decide what counts as knowledge. The apparatus gets to decide what counts as credentialed knowledge, which is a different and smaller thing. The public domain is everything that the apparatus cannot credential away.
Bobby Bress-E is going into the public domain. This is what that looks like.
