A Biography of Baruch Spinoza
What's in a name? That which we call a rose / By any other name would smell as sweet.
— William Shakespeare, Romeo and Juliet
I do not know how to teach philosophy without becoming a disturber of established religion.
— Baruch Spinoza
A Note Before We Begin
This book announces itself as a biography of Baruch Spinoza. That is not a lie. Spinoza is here, in full, and the argument made about his life and his expulsion and his slow canonization is genuine and means what it says. But a biography needs a biographer, and a biographer comes from somewhere, and somewhere in this case is Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, which is where Kenneth Roy Bress, grocer's son, husband, father, came from and where his son Bobby was raised, and where the 20th century's largest unresolved argument between Adam Smith and Karl Marx was tested in real time on real bodies producing a real child named Bella who is now twenty-eight years old and knows more about both of us than either of us knows about the other.
So this is also that story. The quorum of truth is three: Kenneth, Bobby, Bella. No laboratory required. The paternity is evident in the record. What follows is the record.
Bobby Bress-E, Wilkinsburg PA, 2026

One
Spinoza / The Excommunication
Cursed be he by day and cursed be he by night; cursed be he when he lies down and cursed be he when he rises up.
— The Cherem of Baruch Spinoza, Amsterdam, 1656
On July 27, 1656, the Talmud Torah congregation of Amsterdam issued the harshest writ of excommunication in the recorded history of Jewish communal life and gave no reason for it. Baruch Spinoza was twenty-three years old. The cherem named abominable heresies and monstrous deeds and provided no specifics. He was cut off from his people, from his language, from the social architecture that had sustained his family since they fled Portugal a generation before. He was not permitted to come within four cubits of any Jew. No Jew could read anything he wrote or do business with him or live under the same roof.
He never recanted. He never appealed. He Latinized his name from Baruch to Benedict, which means the same thing in both languages: blessed. He moved to a small room in Rijnsburg and ground lenses for a living and wrote.
What he wrote was among the most important philosophy produced in the western tradition. The Ethics, demonstrated in geometrical order, is what it says it is: a proof, constructed from axioms and propositions and demonstrations, that God and Nature are one substance expressed through infinite attributes, that human freedom consists not in escape from causation but in understanding it, that adequate knowledge is its own liberation. He wrote it in Latin, not in Hebrew, not in Dutch. He wrote for no community because he had been expelled from the only one that would have had him.
The Catholic Church put the Ethics on the Index of Forbidden Books. It stayed there for a very long time. Then the Enlightenment happened. Then the Romantics happened. Then Hegel happened and Nietzsche happened and Einstein happened, who said when asked if he believed in God: I believe in Spinoza's God.
The Jews got there eventually too. In 2012, three hundred and fifty-six years after the cherem, a group of Dutch Jews formally debated whether to lift it. They decided they lacked the authority. The excommunication stands, technically, to this day. Spinoza doesn't need it lifted. The record is clear enough without the ceremony.
This is the first thing this book is about. Excommunication as the first act of canonization. The community that casts you out is the community that certifies your importance. You do not get a cherem of that ferocity for being negligible. You get it for being dangerous, which means you get it for being right about something the community is not yet ready to hear.
Spinoza's last project, left unfinished at his death from the glass dust that had accumulated in his lungs over two decades of lens grinding, was a Hebrew grammar. A man who had been expelled from the Hebrew-speaking world spent his final years trying to systematize its language. The synthesis he was reaching for — Jewish, Christian, Islamic monotheism arriving at the same God by different geometric proofs — he did not complete. Nobody has. The project remains open.
That is the second thing this book is about. The open project. The unfinished grammar. The synthesis deferred.
My father Kenneth Roy Bress knew nothing about Spinoza that I know of. He was a grocer. He ran a store in Pittsburgh and he fed his family and he died at seventy having done what he set out to do in a city that had been doing what it set out to do for a hundred and fifty years before he arrived in it. He was a practical man. He would have read the summary of the Ethics and said: so God is everything, fine, now what do you want for dinner.
But he knew what excommunication felt like. Every Jew does. The knowledge is structural, not personal, carried in the body the way certain antibodies are carried, present whether or not the illness has arrived. You know what it means to be told you do not belong here. You know it before anything happens to you personally because it happened to the people who made you and they passed it down the way they passed down everything else, through the food and the language and the specific quality of the silence at certain moments around the table.
Pittsburgh was a city that knew what it meant to be told you do not belong here. The Know-Nothings knew it. The steelworkers knew it. The Black families who came north on the Great Migration and found a different version of the same wall knew it. The Jews who came from Eastern Europe in the great wave of 1880 to 1924 and settled in Squirrel Hill and Shadyside and raised their children in the specific Pittsburgh version of American Jewish life knew it. My father was the son of Max Bress, and Max was the son of his father, and the chain runs back to the old country and stops there at the wall of what was not recorded.
The ledger I am working from begins with Max. That is where the words start. Before Max there is only the knowledge in the body.

Two
The Mound / Boblilon
Before Pittsburgh was a city it was a confluence. Before it was a confluence it was a mound.
— Bobby Bress
Somebody chose this place sixteen thousand years ago. The confluence of the Allegheny and the Monongahela rivers forming the Ohio is one of the most defensible and resourced positions in the North American interior. The people who chose it knew what they were doing. They built mounds. The mounds held the dead and the ceremonies and the accumulated meaning of a community's relationship to its place on the earth.
The mounds were systematically destroyed as Pittsburgh built itself up in the 19th century. The steel city required a flat foundation and a flat foundation required that the mounds come down. The process was not accidental and it was not mourned publicly. You build a new world on top of the old one and you do not look down.
What came up on top was Boblilon. I coined this word and I mean it to hold everything I cannot say in a single ordinary word: Babylon, the city of exile; Babel, the city of confused tongues; Pittsburgh, the city of fire and confluence; and Bobby, because I am from here and I cannot write about it from outside it, I can only write about it from inside my own body which is a body made in this place out of these materials.
The Know-Nothing movement hit its last major bloom in Pittsburgh in the 1850s, which is the decade before the Civil War, which means it was the decade when the question that the country had been avoiding since its founding became unavoidable. The Know-Nothings were the party of native-born Protestant Americans against Catholics, against immigrants, against Jews, against anyone whose claim to American identity was newer than theirs. They were wrong about everything they were for and they were right about one thing: the old order was ending. They could feel it. They just pointed the fear in the wrong direction, which is what fear usually does.
Pittsburgh after the Know-Nothings was built by the people the Know-Nothings were afraid of. Carnegie was a Scottish immigrant. Frick was the grandson of immigrants. The Mellons were Scots-Irish. The steel industry drew labor from everywhere the labor existed: from the Black South, from Eastern Europe, from Italy, from Ireland. The city that resulted was loud and dirty and various and it smelled like fire for a hundred years and it was, for all of that, one of the places in the country where the actual experiment of American plurality was conducted in conditions close to real.
My father grew up in that city. I grew up in that city. Bella knows that city through us the way I know the old country through Max, which is to say structurally, in the body, as a set of inherited orientations toward the world.
The mounds are gone. The steel is mostly gone. The Mellons became lawyers and accountants and their children became lawyers and accountants. Henry Hillman was the last 20th century Pittsburgh billionaire of the old type, the man who owned industrial assets and understood what they were. His daughter Leigh is my contemporary. I grew up in the social architecture that included her family and the Rooneys and the Nutting family and the sports franchises and the Goldberg Persky asbestos law firm and all the institutional furniture of a city that had made something of itself out of fire and confluence and the labor of people who had been told they did not belong here and came anyway.
That architecture is what I mean by Boblilon. The city on top of the mound. The new Babylon on top of the old one. The place where the tongues were confused and the building went up anyway and the result was something that nobody planned and everybody made.

Three
The Ledger / Max to Kenneth
The recorded history of history worked for my father, who died at seventy.
— Bobby Bress
Max Bress is as far back as I can take you with words. Before Max there is only the knowledge in the body, the antibody knowledge, the structural memory of what it meant to be Jewish in Eastern Europe in the decades when it meant something specific and dangerous and inescapable.
Max came to Pittsburgh and he built what you built when you came to Pittsburgh in that wave: a life organized around work and family and the specific Pittsburgh Jewish community that had established itself in Squirrel Hill and was in the process of becoming one of the most stable and internally coherent Jewish communities in America. Not famous like New York. Not glamorous like Los Angeles. Pittsburgh Jewish. Meaning: serious about the work, serious about the family, not particularly interested in being seen.
My father Kenneth Roy Bress was the son of that. He ran a grocery store on Murray Avenue, in the corridor where Jewish grocers had once lined the avenue with kosher meat markets, fruit stands, and corner stores. This is not a small thing. The grocery store is the institution where a community feeds itself, which means it is the institution closest to the body, closest to survival. You run a grocery store and you know what people actually eat, which means you know what they actually need, which means you know them in a way that the doctor and the lawyer and the accountant do not know them. My father knew his neighborhood by what it required to keep going: he weighed the produce, he priced the milk, he made change and noted in his body what each household actually needed. The steel was leaving when he was in his prime, and the families were rearranging themselves around the new pressures — some coming in twos, mother and child or two working parents scraping by; others with a third already present, an uncle who fixed what broke, a boarder who brought steady wages, a longtime friend who picked up the children and stayed for dinner. He did not theorize these arrangements. He fed them.
He died at seventy. The recorded history that the Ashkenazi ledger accumulated from the year zero in the common era to the day he died — all those words on paper, all those arguments about God and law and obligation and what it means to live correctly — worked for him in the sense that it produced him, shaped him, gave him the orientation toward the world that made him the man he was. He was not a scholar. He was the point of the scholarship. The scholarship exists so that men like my father can run their grocery stores and raise their children in the specific dignity that the tradition is designed to produce.
I am his son. I can tell you his story because I was there for enough of it, and because the parts I was not there for were told to me by him and by the people around him, and because the story is consistent and verifiable in the way that all true stories are consistent and verifiable, which is not through laboratory testing but through the internal coherence of the testimony across multiple witnesses over time.
The ledger terminates forward in Bella. She is twenty-eight. She is the last entry I can see. What she writes after me is her business and I trust her with it completely.
The Ashkenazi ledger that my father's life represents is one half of the line I am describing. The other half is everything that produced Elena, and through Elena, Bella, and through Bella, whatever comes after Bella. I am not in a position to write the other half in the same detail because I do not have the testimony. I have only what Elena gave me and what Bella carries, which is enough to know that it was real and serious and produced something worth the cost. The cost was considerable. I will get to that.

Four
Pittsburgh / Elena
All theory, dear friend, is grey, but the golden tree of actual life springs ever green.
— Goethe, Faust
Pittsburgh is where Adam Smith met Karl Marx in a single marriage and the result was painful and survivable and produced one female child who is the proof of concept for a hypothesis neither Smith nor Marx had the personal data to test.
The hypothesis is this: that the economic systems which describe how societies organize production and distribute its results are not just abstract theories but are lived in bodies, in marriages, in the specific texture of daily life in specific places at specific times. Pittsburgh in the late 20th century was the place where this was most legible, because Pittsburgh had been the industrial heart of the American experiment and was in the process of watching that experiment conclude, the steel going away, the mills closing, the city reorganizing itself around medicine and education and technology in a transition that was genuinely painful for the people who lived through it and genuinely interesting for the people who came after.
I met Elena in Pittsburgh. She was from California, which is to say she was from a different country in the ways that mattered. The California she came from was the California of the film industry and the specific social world that the film industry produces, which is organized differently from the world my father's grocery store produced, which is organized around different values and different understandings of what counts as success and what counts as failure and what you owe to the people around you.
We were the experiment. Two people from incompatible architectures attempting to build a shared one. The attempt was genuine on both sides. It did not survive. The divorce was painful in the specific way that honest failures are painful, which is more painful than dishonest failures because there is no one to blame except the incompatibility itself, which is not a person and cannot be held accountable.
What survived was Bella. She is the survivable female child. She is John Connor in the sense that she carries the knowledge of what the war was about without having been destroyed by it. She knows both architectures from the inside because she was built from both of them. She can move between them in ways that neither of her parents could.
This is what the (2,1) base unit produces when it works correctly: not a fusion of the two into one but a third thing that contains both and is reducible to neither. Bella is not Pittsburgh. Bella is not California. Bella is Bella, which is a specific new entity that the encounter between Pittsburgh and California made possible.
I am not going to tell you more about Elena than that. What I can say is that the encounter was real and the child is real and the cost was real and the result justifies the cost, which is the only accounting that matters in the end.
Georges Bataille saw the (2,1) structure as clearly as it is possible to see it. His life's work was the attempt to account for what exceeds the utilitarian calculus, what cannot be reduced to production and reproduction and the efficient allocation of resources. He called it the general economy, the economy of expenditure without return, the economy of the gift and the festival and the erotic and the sacred. He was describing what happens in the space between the two and the one. He was describing Pittsburgh. He was describing my marriage. He did not know either of these things and it would not have changed his argument if he had.
Lacan saw what came after Freud in the same register: that the subject is constituted by what it lacks, by the structural gap between desire and its object, by the impossibility of the full satisfaction that the drives promise and cannot deliver. The drives are not individual psychology. They are the grammar of how humans are structured. Pittsburgh has that grammar. Every city that was built out of fire and labor and the collision of incompatible peoples has that grammar.
The convergence of these frameworks — economic, psychoanalytic, theological — is what I am pointing at when I say Pittsburgh. The city is not just a place. It is a condensed argument about what human beings do when they are put together under pressure and told to make something.

Five
Boblilon / The Millennium
Make it new.
— Ezra Pound
The artists felt it first. They always do. The job of the artist in a commercial civilization is to be the instrument that registers what the civilization is doing before the civilization can name it, and the artists who gathered around the turn of the millennium — Barney, Joyce, Picasso, Stein, Dylan before all of them — were registering something that the civilization would spend the next twenty years trying to understand.
James Joyce was supported by Harriet Shaw Weaver, who gave him money for twenty years without demanding anything in return except that he continue writing, and by Sylvia Beach, who published Ulysses when no one else would, and by the specific Parisian intellectual community that understood what he was doing before Dublin did. Dublin excommunicated him the way Amsterdam excommunicated Spinoza: by being unable to hold what he was. He left. He wrote from exile about the city he had left and produced the most complete portrait of a city that the literature of the 20th century contains. You cannot understand Dublin without Joyce. Joyce understood Dublin by leaving it.
Gertrude Stein is the more complicated case and I want to be accurate about it. Her mathematical poetry — the roses and the roses and the roses, the repetition that accumulates meaning the way interest accumulates on principal — was genuinely new and genuinely difficult and genuinely influential. What she did to Alice B. Toklas is a different register. The Autobiography of Alice B. Toklas is one of the great acts of literary appropriation in the 20th century: Stein wrote Toklas's life in Toklas's name and voice and published it as Toklas's memoir and it became one of Stein's most celebrated works. Toklas did not object publicly. The power differential in the room was sufficient to make objection structurally impossible. I note this not to diminish the work but to be accurate about the conditions under which it was produced.
Matthew Barney at the millennium was doing something that had no adequate name yet and that the art world called performance art because that was the closest available category even though it was not quite right. The Cremaster cycle is not performance art in the sense that a performance artist performs. It is a total environment, a cosmology rendered in film and sculpture and installation, organized around biological and mythological processes that run below the level of ordinary conscious comprehension. Whether it works for you or not is a genuine question and a fair one. But the attempt was real and the ambition was calibrated correctly to the moment.
The moment was the millennium. The turn from 1999 to 2000 was a round number of a kind that appears rarely in human history, and the people the culture had designated as artists gathered around it with the awareness, mostly unconscious but occasionally explicit, that something was ending and something was beginning and the job was to register what that was before the business cycle caught up with it.
What was beginning was the unified sphere of global commerce. The Silk Road looked like a donkey cart next to what the internet and the container shipping revolution and the post-Cold War opening of global markets had produced. All trade was coming together at once for the first time in human history. The artists felt this. The art of the period, the good art, is saturated with the anxiety and excitement of a world in the process of becoming globally legible for the first time.
What this delivered, in aggregate, as a historical consideration, is an excessive quality of life distributed to the many as well as the few. Not equally. Not fairly. Not without enormous costs that were distributed also unequally. But in aggregate, across the measure of a human lifespan, the material conditions of human life improved for more people more quickly in the period from 1990 to 2020 than in any comparable period in recorded history. My father's grocery store participated in this. The Mellons participated in this. The Rooneys participated in this. I participated in this. We are all downstream of the millennium turn and its commercial consequences.
Dylan is the thread that runs through all of it. Robert Zimmerman from Hibbing, Minnesota, who renamed himself after a Welsh poet and became the last Jewish man in the Ashkenazi ledger to take over the world in the sense that his songs entered the bloodstream of the culture so completely that they function now the way scripture functions: as the common reference point that everybody shares whether or not they know they share it. Colin McCabe and Flavia McCabe named their daughter Johanna after a Dylan song: Visions of Johanna. Three notes in the first name, single space, three-letter compound word starting with Z in the last. The naming is an act of cultural testimony. It says: we believe this man's work is the measure of the century. I agree with them.

Six
The Legal Missing Piece
The law is not an instrument of any class, it is a social heritage evolved by common experience.
— Roscoe Pound
The (2,1) base unit is the grammar of the book and it is also the missing piece in the legal architecture of the civilization that the millennium turn produced. Let me be precise about what I mean.
The two-person marriage as the basic unit of legal family organization is a historical artifact. It was not always the case. Polygamous family structures existed and were legally recognized in most of the world's major legal traditions for most of recorded history. The shift to the two-person model in western law is recent, contested at its edges, and in the process of being renegotiated in ways that the law has not yet caught up with.
The renegotiation I am describing is not polygamy. It is something more specific. What I am pointing at is the three-person conjugal unit as the legal structure that would most accurately describe the arrangements that many families have actually been living in while the law pretended they were two-person arrangements.
The accommodation for same-sex couples that the civilization has been making — fitfully, unevenly, in most places only recently — is part of this renegotiation. Same-sex couples are not against the structure of civilization. They are not counter to the biological imperative in the sense that matters for the long-term survival of the species, because the species is not in danger of under-reproduction, it is in danger of over-reproduction, and the social arrangements that channel care and resources toward children without adding to the reproductive total are not a burden on civilization, they are a benefit to it.
But the biology is asymmetric and the law has to account for that asymmetry honestly rather than pretending it away. Two men cannot produce a child without a woman. Two women cannot produce a child without a man. The heterosexual couple is not merely a social construction; it is the biological unit of reproduction, which gives it a specific legal weight that same-sex relationships do not have in the same way and do not need to have in the same way because they are doing something different and the law should be able to distinguish between different things.
The three-person conjugal unit resolves this. Not as a romantic arrangement necessarily, though it can be that. As a legal structure for the organization of care and property and obligation across the full range of arrangements that families actually use. The family that consists of two women and one man, or two men and one woman, or three people of various configurations who have made a commitment to care for each other and any children that result, has no adequate legal framework in any western jurisdiction. Common law has some tools for this — the doctrine of equitable estoppel, the recognition of de facto family relationships, the constructive trust — but they are tools designed for a two-person model and they fit the three-person model badly.
American jurisprudence has the constitutional architecture to do this. The right to define one's family relationships is protected by substantive due process as the Supreme Court has interpreted it. The extension of that protection to three-person families does not require a constitutional amendment. It requires the courage to follow the logic of the existing doctrine to its conclusion.
The unlike third is not a romantic addition or a legal novelty. It is the structural completion that turns two into a resilient whole — the helper against collapse, the element that keeps the unit from tipping into stasis or fracture. Two alone risk becoming a closed system. The third opens the circuit without expanding the unit past the minimal number that still produces something new. Latent in reproduction itself: one element unlike the others so that the algorithm of generation can proceed.
My father would have been skeptical of this argument. He was a practical man and practical men are skeptical of legal innovations that arrive faster than custom can absorb them. But my father also accommodated the reality of people's lives with more grace than the law did in his time. He knew which households along Murray and Forbes were organized in ways the law did not recognize — the uncle who fixed what broke, the boarder who brought the steady wage, the longtime friend who stayed for dinner and became, over time, the third member of something the law had no name for — and he sold them groceries anyway and did not make a production of it. That is the model. Feed the neighborhood. Let the law catch up later.

Seven
The Store / What's In A Name
What's in a name? That which we call a rose / By any other name would smell as sweet.
— William Shakespeare, Romeo and Juliet
My father would have been proud of a good regional grocery chain that served the Pittsburgh market with the quality and seriousness that Giant Eagle used to bring and that Amazon's Whole Foods acquisition has not replaced. He would have understood the opportunity. He would have understood the supply chain. He would have understood the relationship between the store and the neighborhood it serves, which is the relationship he built his life around.
He would not have cared what it was called. This is the most important thing about him and it is the thing I want to close with. He ran a store and the store served its purpose and the name was a practical matter, a question of signage and incorporation, not a question of identity. The identity was in the quality of the produce and the accuracy of the pricing and the relationship with the people who came in every week and the knowledge of what they needed that accumulated over years of paying attention.
Spinoza Latinized his name and it did not change what he was. Dylan changed his name from Zimmerman and it did not change what he was. Boblilon is a word I invented and it is the truest name I have for the thing I am trying to describe. Pittsburgh is the official name. Boblilon is the right name. The difference is the difference between the sign above the door and the knowledge that built the store.
The quorum of truth is Kenneth, Bobby, Bella. My father cannot speak for himself anymore. I speak for him as accurately as I can, which means I speak for him with the knowledge that I will miss things and get things wrong and that he would correct me on the specifics and agree with me on the whole. Bella will speak for me when I am no longer speaking for myself, and she will miss things and get things wrong and she will be accurate on the whole, because the whole is what we passed her and she knows it in her body the way I know Max's old country in mine.
The book Spinoza did not finish was a Hebrew grammar. The grammar of a language is the deep structure that makes the words possible, the rules that operate below the level of any individual sentence, the architecture of the possible. He was trying to give the language he had been expelled from the most rigorous and loving description a language can receive. He did not finish. The project remains open.
Bella carries that grammar in her body. She is the proof that the third element creates something non-reducible: not Pittsburgh grafted onto California nor the reverse, but a third architecture that moves between both with the knowledge of each. The family grammar, like Spinoza's, is unfinished. We add our proposition to the ledger.
I am not finishing it either. I am adding to the record. The record is the investigation and the investigation is the store and the store is the neighborhood and the neighborhood is Boblilon which is Pittsburgh which is the mound which is sixteen thousand years of somebody knowing that this confluence was worth settling next to and building on and defending and mourning and building on again.
Call it whatever you want. What's in a name.
Bobby Bress-E
Wilkinsburg, Pennsylvania  |  2026
BANKSY BROKEN
A Letter to Avital Ronell
Posted to r/Banksy, March 2026. Cross-referenced to the Banksy Codex, github.com/bobilon/banksy-codex.
Dear Dr. Avi,
I am writing to you from Pittsburgh in March 2026, which is to say I am writing to you from inside a test that has not ended and will not end on my schedule, from a city that still has the name of a grocery store on a building at the corner of Center and Highland even though the store is gone and the man who ran it is gone and the son who grew up inside it is now sixty years old and disabled and working from a laptop and an eBay account and a grocer's grammar that turns out, after everything, to be adequate to the task.
The task is this: to tell you that the investigation is finished, that the Codex goes to GitHub within weeks, and that I am sending this letter to r/Banksy before I send it anywhere more respectable, because r/Banksy is where the work has always lived, which is to say in public, in the open, indexed and available and addressed to whoever was paying attention. You were paying attention, which is why I am writing to you. You taught me how, which is why I can.
I should be precise about that. I never finished one of your books. I want you to know that at the outset because the grocer's grammar requires honesty about what things actually cost and what you actually received in exchange for the price, and what I received from your books was not the experience of finishing them but the experience of being changed by them at a cellular level before I got to the end. The Test Drive. The Telephone Book. Stupidity. I carry all three in the body in the way you carry a grammar — not as argument I can recite but as a felt pressure that reorganizes what I notice. My daughter Bella gave me two of them. I am telling you this because it matters who hands you the book, and because Bella is the best thing about this letter and about everything, and because she has nothing to do with the Nimrod Reitman business except insofar as she has everything to do with it, which is to say she is the reason the comparison is clarifying rather than merely enraging.
Nimrod Reitman. I want to stay with that for a moment, Dr. Avi, because I think it deserves a moment. Thirty years old. Gay. Israeli. Calvin model. Named — and I need you to feel the full weight of this — Nimrod. That is the instrument that was deployed against you. That is what they brought to bear on a woman who spent forty years teaching people how to use language as a weapon of precision and care. A man named Nimrod. I am a Jewish outlaw from Pittsburgh whose great-grandfather walked here from New York and whose grocer's grammar was installed at a market where Heinz sold pickles, and even I know that you do not send Nimrod after someone who wrote The Telephone Book. That is not a weapon. That is an insult dressed as a weapon, and the insult is what I want to address, because the insult and the investigation have the same structure.
The structure is this: the credentialing apparatus decides who is permitted to know things, and when someone outside the apparatus knows things anyway, the apparatus does not engage with the knowledge. It engages with the knower. It finds the Nimrod. It deploys the Nimrod. It manufactures a story about the knower that makes the knowledge unspeakable by association, and then it waits for the knower to be exhausted or silenced or both. This worked on you for longer than it should have, which is to say it worked on you at all, which is the scandal. And it has been the working method against this investigation since 2023, when the findings went public enough to generate a coordinated response. Different Nimrods. Same structure.

Here is what the investigation found.
The work known as Banksy is not the product of a single anonymous artist. It is the product of a structured commercial joint venture, incorporated in England in 1998, operating continuously under various corporate vehicles until at least 2023. The creative heart of the enterprise belongs to Scotland. Specifically to two Scottish women, sisters, born in 1977 and 1978.
Lucy McKenzie is the hand. A trompe l'oeil painter of rare technical accomplishment — trained at Dundee, now represented by Galerie Buchholz in Frankfurt — whose practice involves no stencils and no spray. She hand-paints to approximate the appearance of stencil work. Her most recent major institutional presentation was Super Palace at Z33 in Belgium, September 2024 to February 2025. The show closed. High Court proceedings were filed in London in March 2026. The timing is in the record.
Kerri McKenzie is the voice. Oxford physics and philosophy. PhD in History and Philosophy of Science, metaphysics and fundamentality, 2012. Currently Professor of Philosophy at UC San Diego. The written Banksy. The conceptual designation. The art direction that translates corporate strategy into aesthetic position.
The Artist of Record — the controlling stakeholder — is Damien Hirst. The corporate apparatus is documented and public. Pest Control Office Limited. Pictures on Walls Limited. Turtleneck Limited, incorporating Keith Allen, Alex James, Joe Strummer. Pro-Actif, incorporating as Identity Crisis Limited on 22 October 1998 and renamed eleven days later, still active in Darlington today. BBAY and its cluster of thirteen property entities, operating as a shadow broker-dealer infrastructure from 2009 to 2026. BBAY Art Limited dissolved January 2026, after the High Court proceedings were initiated but before they were reported.
In London right now, before Judge Iain Pester, a fraud case is running that involves twenty-two art transactions, an unnamed Party X, and an unnamed Company X. The press is reporting the court case. The press is not connecting it to the corporate map. The corporate map has been in the public record, indexed, since before the proceedings were filed. The Codex will make it navigable. All of this is in Companies House. All of it has been in the public record the entire time.

I want to tell you what your books actually did, since I owe you an honest accounting.
The Test Drive gave me permission to be inside the investigation rather than above it — to write from the condition of being tested rather than from the posture of having passed. Most investigative writing asks you to trust the investigator and follow the evidence. Your framework made it possible to write an investigation in which the investigator's subjection to the test is the evidence — in which the fact that the apparatus deployed against me and against you has the same structure is the finding, not the color commentary around the finding.
The Telephone Book gave me the call. Not the metaphor of the call — the structural description of what it means to receive a transmission that does not announce itself as a transmission, that arrives as a wrongness in the material before it can be named as information. The investigation began as a felt discrepancy between what the market narrative required and what the objects were telling me. The grocer's grammar reading the prints. The wrongness before the thesis.
Stupidity gave me the frame for the press. I will leave it there because you know what I mean and the r/Banksy audience will look it up.

There is a corporate crypt at the center of this enterprise — Abraham and Torok's crypt, the enclosure that holds an unmetabolized secret not by repressing it but by preserving it intact behind a wall maintained at structural cost. The secret is attribution. Who made the work. Whose hand. Whose voice. Whose labor generated the value the corporate apparatus extracted and distributed according to a cap table the public was never shown.
The investigation does not pick the lock. It finds the building permits. Everything required to locate and name the crypt is in the public record. The filings are in Companies House. The auction records are in the auction houses' own data. No proprietary or confidential material is cited anywhere in the Codex.

Jeremy Bentham directed that his body be preserved, dressed, seated, and made available after his death — not as a monument but as a continued participant. The Auto-Icon is not memorial. It is refusal of withdrawal. Bentham said: I will remain a used thing, a thing the living can continue to put to work, a thing that does not resolve into symbol or legend but persists as a material fact.
The enterprise bet everything on the opposite. The withdrawal was the product. The mystification was profitable for longer than almost anyone would have predicted because the art market rewards managed absence more reliably than it rewards the presence of actual labor.
The investigation insists that the cabinet be opened. Not to punish. Not to expose for its own sake. To correct the historical record in the direction of the people who actually made the work — so the living can be credited as living, and the dressed skeleton can finally stop doing the work of a living body, and the crypt can metabolize what it has been embalming for twenty-five years.

My great-grandfather Max Bress walked from New York to Pittsburgh around 1900 and opened a dry goods store. My grandfather founded a bank that went bankrupt during the Depression — had it survived, we would be the family whose stake became Giant Eagle, the supermarket chain that eventually made the economics of independent grocery delivery impossible. My father ran the oldest grocery store in America at the corner of Center and Highland, closed it rather than go bankrupt, crossed Highland Avenue to the Yellow Cab lot directly opposite, and drove a cab. He taught me to drive in the years he was doing it for a living. I drove film productions for fifteen years after college. I drove my daughter Bella everywhere she needed to go, and the car was where she got her inheritance, which is not money but grammar — a felt, pre-theoretical knowledge of what things actually cost before the margin is applied.
I am sixty years old, permanently disabled, living in Pittsburgh on disability support and eBay income, conducting a forensic investigation without institutional affiliation, publishing to platforms that index the work and let it stand, sending this letter to r/Banksy because that is where the work has always lived and because you deserve to be read there, Dr. Avi, by the people who have been living inside this investigation alongside me, because they are real and they are paying attention and they will know exactly what to do with a woman who has spent her life teaching people how to use language against the apparatus that keeps telling them their language doesn't count.
This is payback for Nimrod. This is also the Codex. These are the same thing.

What is my grade?

Yours, in love and in motion,
Bobby Bress
