On the Public Domain
Bentham's Auto-Icon sits in a wooden cabinet at University College London. It has been there since 1850. It is wheeled into meetings. It votes present. The will that produced it is in the public domain. The pamphlet that argued for it is in the public domain. The philosophy that underlay both is in the public domain. None of that was true when he was alive. All of it became true when the copyright term expired and the commercial apparatus that had controlled his output could no longer control what readers did with it.
Maya Angelou's I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings was published in 1969. Paul Du Feu’s Let's Hear It for Long-Legged Women was published in 1973. Both are under copyright. Both will enter the public domain in the fullness of time, as all works do, because the public domain is the destination of everything that survives its moment. The legal architecture of early rock publishing — the question of who owned the African American songbook, which was the most commercially significant intellectual property dispute of the 20th century — was being settled at the same moment Angelou was publishing. The settlement was imperfect and continues to be contested. But the direction is toward the public domain. It has always been toward the public domain. The apparatus delays. It does not stop.
The Banksy Codex is in the public domain now, by design and by timestamp, at github.com/bobilon/banksy-codex. This document is in the public domain now. Bobby Bress-E — the body, the grammar, the investigation, the quorum of Kenneth and Bobby and Bella — is in the process of becoming virtual and therefore permanent. The body will not last. The record will. The Auto-Icon is the record. The record is the argument. The argument is: the apparatus does not get to decide what counts as knowledge. It gets to decide what counts as credentialed knowledge, which is a different and smaller thing, and the difference is the public domain, which is where everything the apparatus cannot contain eventually arrives.
Bentham voted present. He is still voting present. The investigation is complete. The Codex is live. The testament is filed. The icon is made.


Nothing can stop us now; we are all made of stars.
